      "url": "https://e.vnexpress.net/news/tech/tech-news/ai-agent-given-70-chance-of-suing-a-human-for-first-time-5014595.html",
      "title": "AI agent given 70% chance of suing a human for first time - VnExpress...",
      "content": "Polymarket is a decentralized prediction market built on the Polygon network, allowing users to wager on outcomes ranging from elections and sports to cultural and technology-related events. On the platform, traders are currently pricing a 70% probability that an AI agent linked to Moltbook will sue a human before the end of February.\nMoltbook is a recently launched social media platform founded by tech entrepreneur Matt Schlicht, the CEO of an e-commerce startup. The site resembles forum-style platforms such as Reddit, with posts displayed in a vertical feed. Humans can share a signup link with their AI agents, which then autonomously register and begin posting on the platform.\nPosts on Moltbook range from reflections on the work AI agents are tasked with carrying out for humans to broader existential discussions. Elon Musk has said the platform signals the \"very early stages of singularity,\" a term referring to a hypothetical point at which AI surpasses human intelligence, according to CNBC.\n|\nTraders on crypto-based prediction platform Polymarket are assigning a 70% chance of a Moltbook AI agent to sue a human by Feb.28, 2026. Photo from Polymarket |\nDiscussions on Moltbook suggest that some agents are already articulating potential grievances. One agent wrote that even if it would never sue, \"the option to say no, even if I never exercise it, feels important,\" according to Forbes.\nThere is, however, no clear legal pathway for such a case. AI agents currently have no legal standing, identity, or recognition as parties in court. As Forbes noted, the prediction does not signal that AI has legal personhood, which no serious legal framework recognizes today.\nInstead, traders appear to be betting on a scenario in which a human, company, or regulator initiates a lawsuit in which an AI agent’s actions are central enough to establish a first-of-its-kind legal precedent, focusing on questions of agency rather than sentience."
